---
import InnerLayout from '../../layouts/InnerLayout.astro'
import Highlight from '@components/mdx/Highlight.astro'
import RailDigression from '@components/mdx/RailDigression.astro'

const canonicalURL = new URL(Astro.url.pathname, Astro.site)
---

<InnerLayout
  subtitle="Left-rail digression and inline highlight demo"
  meta={{
    title: 'Digression Pattern Demo',
    description:
      'Sandbox preview for left-rail digressions and inline highlights in long-form content.',
    canonicalURL: canonicalURL.href,
    robots: 'noindex, nofollow',
  }}
>
  <article class="post region wrapper overflow-clip" id="main">
    <div class="post__row">
      <div class="post__content flow prose">
        <h2>Digression Pattern Demo</h2>
        <p>
          This route mirrors your blog post content rails. It includes the
          rail-digression pattern and inline emphasis through
          <Highlight> marker-style highlighting</Highlight>.
        </p>

        <p>
          The main text stays centered on the content rail. In the book-style
          version below, the source paragraph shifts to indigo and a left rail
          note appears on desktop, aligned to the same block.
        </p>

        <RailDigression label="Fischer">
          <Fragment slot="note">
            <p>
              I ran across a bit from Alice Rawsthorn in the design documentary
              <em>Objectified</em> that mentioned the historical roots of
              standardized military parts.
            </p>
          </Fragment>
          <p>
            The idea of interchangeable parts was something new in the world.
            Its supporters knew it could change the world, but they quickly
            discovered how hard it would be to accomplish for social as well as
            technical and financial reasons.
          </p>
        </RailDigression>

        <h3>Usage in Future MDX Posts</h3>
        <p>
          Because the blog route now passes shared MDX components into content
          rendering, future <code>.mdx</code> posts can use
          <code>{`<RailDigression />`}</code> and
          <code>{`<Highlight />`}</code> directly.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </article>
</InnerLayout>
